I think I've narrowed down the source of the error. I believe the following line in GameObject::Render might be causing it:

material->CreateDescriptorSet(renderer.CreateDescriptorSetLayout(), renderer.CreateDescriptorPool(1), mvpBuffer, sizeof(MVP));

It runs this line for every render call.

Yes, that's very likely the reason behind the issue you're facing.

In the provided code, the `CreateDescriptorSet` function of `Material` class is being called for every frame, and with every call, a new descriptor set layout and a new descriptor pool are created. 

To fix this issue, create the descriptor set layout and descriptor pool during Material or scene initialization, store them as member variables in the appropriate class, and then use the stored layouts and pools while rendering. Updating the descriptor set bindings should not require creating a new layout every time.

For example, you can store the descriptor set layout and descriptor pool in the `Material` or `Scene` class and pass them to the `Render` function of the `GameObject` class for each frame.

1. Add member variables to the `Material` class:

```cpp
private:
    ...
    VkDescriptorSetLayout descriptorSetLayout;
    VkDescriptorPool descriptorPool;
```

2. Initialize them in the `Material::Initialize` function:

```cpp
void Material::Initialize(...)
{
    ...
    this->descriptorSetLayout = descriptorSetLayout;
    this->descriptorPool = descriptorPool;
    ...
}
```

3. Modify the `GameObject::Render` function to use the stored descriptor set layout and descriptor pool:

```cpp
void GameObject::Render(Renderer& renderer, const Camera& camera)
{
    ...
    material->UpdateBufferBinding(mvpBuffer, renderer.GetDevice(), sizeof(MVP));
    ...
}
```

4. Modify the `Material::UpdateBufferBinding` function to use the stored descriptor set layout and descriptor pool instead of creating new ones each time:

```cpp
void Material::UpdateBufferBinding(VkBuffer newBuffer, VkDevice device, VkDeviceSize devicesize)
{
    ...
    CreateDescriptorSet(descriptorSetLayout, descriptorPool, newBuffer, devicesize);
    ...
}
```

By making these changes, you will ensure that the descriptor set layout and descriptor pool are only created once per material rather than per frame. This should resolve the issue of not destroying descriptor set layouts properly and improve the performance of your application.

